# Git: incremental commits

## Expectation

- Prefer **many small commits** over one large “dump” commit. Each commit should be a **single logical step** someone can understand from the message alone—**no dependency on the original chat**.
- A good commit: **reversible** with `git revert` (or easy bisect), **builds/tests pass** at that point when CI exists.

## Scope per commit (examples)

- One focused change: “add protocol SessionStart type”, “wire daemon stdio framing”, “extension: spawn child process”.
- If a feature spans multiple packages, either **commit in layers** (protocol → core → daemon → extension) or **one commit per package** with a shared prefix: `feat(ask): …`.

## Commit messages

- Use a **conventional** prefix when helpful: `feat:`, `fix:`, `docs:`, `chore:`, `refactor:`.
- **Body optional**; include **why** when the diff alone is unclear (migration, protocol version bump, workaround).

## Anti-patterns

- “WIP everything” before push unless you are truly experimental—**squash only** before merge if policy requires; still keep **local** incremental commits until then.
- Mixing unrelated refactors with feature code in the same commit.

## Agent workflow

- After a coherent slice of work, **commit** instead of leaving a dirty tree across unrelated files.
- If unsure split vs single commit: default to **split** when the diff touches **unrelated concerns** (e.g. docs + core logic can be two commits: `docs:` then `feat:`).
